  <h1>ADA Violation Types</h1>
  <p><em>Reviewed by Riley Chen (RC), Employment &amp; Civil Rights Practice Lead. Updated May 2026.</em></p>
  <h2>Title I &mdash; Employment</h2>
  <p>Covers employers with 15 or more employees. Prohibits discrimination in hiring, firing, promotions, pay, job assignments, training, and all other terms and conditions of employment. The most litigated ADA violations:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Failure to provide reasonable accommodation</strong> &mdash; denying modified schedule, leave, remote work, or other accommodation without demonstrating undue hardship.</li>
    <li><strong>Wrongful termination</strong> &mdash; firing an employee because of disability or for requesting accommodation.</li>
    <li><strong>Failure to hire</strong> &mdash; rejecting a qualified applicant because of disability or perceived disability.</li>
    <li><strong>Disability harassment</strong> &mdash; a pattern of conduct that creates a hostile work environment based on disability.</li>
    <li><strong>Retaliation</strong> &mdash; adverse action against an employee who filed an ADA complaint, requested accommodation, or participated in an investigation.</li>
  </ul>
  <h2>Title II &mdash; State and Local Government</h2>
  <p>Covers all programs, activities, and services of state and local governments regardless of size. Common violations: inaccessible government buildings, inaccessible websites and digital services, failure to provide effective communication (sign language interpreters, accessible formats), and exclusion from government programs.</p>
  <h2>Title III &mdash; Public Accommodations</h2>
  <p>Covers businesses and nonprofits that serve the public (hotels, restaurants, retail stores, theaters, hospitals, law offices, gyms). Requires removal of barriers where readily achievable, provision of auxiliary aids, and policy modifications for people with disabilities. Website accessibility has become a major area of Title III litigation.</p>
  <h2>Perceived disability claims</h2>
  <p>The ADA also protects people <em>regarded as</em> having a disability, even if they don&rsquo;t have one. If an employer acts based on a perceived impairment, the claim proceeds under the ADA without needing to prove an actual disability.</p>
  <h2>Where to go from here</h2>
  <p>See <a href="/guides/how-ada-damages-are-calculated">how ADA damages are calculated</a> and <a href="/guides/what-to-do-after-ada-violation">what to do after an ADA violation</a>.</p>
</BaseLayout>
